{{multiple issues|over detailed=September 2011|technical=September 2011}}
[[Image:closedrestaurant.jpg|thumb|400px||A closed restaurant in [[Gananoque, Ontario]]]]

'''Commercial insolvency in Canada''' has options and procedures that are distinct from those available in consumer [[insolvency]] proceedings. It is governed by the following statutes:

:* The ''[[Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act]]'' ("BIA") <ref>{{Cite web|title = Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act (R.S.C., 1985, c. B-3) | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/index.html | accessdate = 2011-08-25}}</ref>
:* The ''[[Companies' Creditors Arrangements Act]]'' ("CCAA") <ref>{{Cite web|title = Companies' Creditors Arrangements Act (R.S.C., 1985, c. C-36) | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-36/index.html | accessdate = 2011-08-25}}</ref>
:* The ''Winding-Up and Restructuring Act'' <ref>{{Cite web|title = Winding-up and Restructuring Act (R.S.C., 1985, c. W-11) | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/W-11/index.html | accessdate = 2011-08-25}}</ref>

The following discussion concentrates on insolvency as it applies to corporations, but the rules apply to individuals and other entities involved in commercial matters as well, with necessary modifications.

==Financial difficulties prior to insolvency==

Provincial legislation under the [[property and civil rights]] power of the [[Constitution Act, 1867]] regulates the resolution of financial difficulties that occur before the onset of insolvency, and the BIA incorporates many of them by reference in the application of its provisions. Notable legislation is in effect for governing:

* absconding debtors<ref>{{Cite web|title = Absconding Debtors Act (Ontario), R.S.O. 1990, c. A.2 | url = http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_90a02_e.htm}}</ref>
* [[bulk sales]] (in Ontario and Newfoundland only)<ref>{{Cite web|title = Bulk Sales Act (Ontario), R.S.O. 1990, c. B.14 | url = http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_elaws_statutes_90b14_e.htm}}</ref>
* [[fraudulent conveyance]]s<ref>{{Cite web|title = Fraudulent Conveyances Act (Ontario), R.S.O. 1990, c. F.29 | url = http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_90f29_e.htm}}</ref>
* relief of creditors<ref>{{Cite web|title = Creditors<U+2019> Relief Act, 2010 (Ontario) , S.O. 2010, c. 16, Sch. 4 | url = http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_10c16b_e.htm}}</ref>
* seizure of assets<ref>{{Cite web|title = Execution Act (Ontario), R.S.O. 1990, c. E.24 | url = http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_90e24_e.htm}}</ref>

==Alternatives to resolving financial difficulties==

Where a commercial debtor is experiencing financial difficulties, it is generally in his best interests to work with the secured lenders.<ref>{{Cite web|author = D. Robb English, Paul Bowers and David Carson |title = Turnarounds: Dealing with the Secured Lender | url= http://www.airdberlis.com/Templates/Articles/articleFiles/315/Turnaround_seminar.pdf | publisher = [[Aird & Berlis]] | date = 2004-09-27/28 | accessdate = 2011-09-13}}</ref> The following options may be considered in order to seek a resolution to the matter:

* informal compromise with creditors
* out-of court [[restructuring|restructuring agreements]] <ref>{{Cite web|author = Milly Chow |title = Out-of-Court Restructurings | url= http://www.blakes.com/english/view_bulletin.asp?ID=4342 | publisher = [[Blake, Cassels & Graydon]] | date = 2010-11-16 | accessdate = 2011-09-07}}</ref>
* plans of arrangement under the [[Canada Business Corporations Act]] or similar provincial corporations legislation <ref>{{Cite web|title = CBCA, S. 192 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-44/page-64.html}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Policy Concerning Arrangements Under Section 192 of the CBCA | url= https://www.ic.gc.ca/eic/site/cd-dgc.nsf/eng/cs01073.html | publisher = Industry Canada | date = 2010-01-04 | accessdate = 2011-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web | author = Peter Rubin |title = Arrangement Provisions of the Canada Business Corporations Act | url= http://www.blakes.com/english/view_bulletin.asp?ID=4341 | publisher = [[Blake, Cassels & Graydon]] | date = 2010-11-16 | accessdate = 2011-09-07}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Restructuring Under the Business Corporations Act | url= http://www.fmc-law.com/upload/en/publications/Restructuring%20Under%20the%20Business%20Corporations%20Act_Sept09.pdf | publisher = [[Fraser Milner Casgrain]] | date = 2009-09 | accessdate = 2011-09-08}}</ref>
* the debtor making an assignment for the general benefit of creditors under the pertinent provincial legislation <ref>{{Cite web|title = Assignments and Preferences Act (Ontario), R.S.O. 1990, c. A.33 | url= http://www.e-laws.gov.on.ca/html/statutes/english/elaws_statutes_90a33_e.htm | accessdate = 2011-09-13}}</ref>
* the creditor(s) securing appointment of a [[Receivership|receiver or interim receiver]] to seize and administer any of the debtor's property <ref>{{Cite web| author = Aubrey E. Kaufman and R. Graham Phoenix |title = Interim Receivers under the BIA: What practicality demands ... for now | url = http://www.fasken.com/files/Publication/b2d58d89-0bad-44a6-97b2-14f728357d13/Presentation/PublicationAttachment/85794bc1-84d1-4461-8af8-2521f3590497/Interim_Receivers_Under_the_BIA.pdf| publisher = [[Fasken Martineau]] | date = 2007-10-31 | accessdate = 2011-09-12}}</ref>
* the debtor making a proposal to creditors (known as a "Division I proposal") <ref>{{Cite web|title = Process for Division I Proposals | url = http://www.ic.gc.ca/eic/site/bsf-osb.nsf/eng/br02052.html | publisher = OSB | accessdate = 2011-08-25}}</ref>
* the debtor making an application under the CCAA to make a compromise or arrangement with its creditors <ref>{{Cite web|title = The Companies<U+2019> Creditors Arrangement Act | url = http://www.ic.gc.ca/eic/site/bsf-osb.nsf/eng/br02284.html | publisher = OSB | accessdate = 2011-08-25}}</ref>
* an insolvent debtor making an assignment under the BIA for the general benefit of his creditors<ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, S. 49 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-23.html#h-22}}</ref>
* creditors applying for a bankruptcy order where the debtor owes at least $1,000 and has committed an act of bankruptcy

All options other than the first four have the effect of staying any proceedings that can be brought against the debtor.

Insolvent persons have the choice of making an assignment immediately, or to seek protection from creditors in order to reorganize their affairs and continue as a going concern. For the latter option, companies owing less than $5 million generally opt to file a Division I proposal, while those owing more can also opt for the CCAA proceeding.

==Entities subject to insolvency regime==

The BIA covers all debtor and insolvent persons, and "person" includes (in addition to individuals):

* partnerships (including one or more of the partners, upon the creditor's application) <ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, S. 43(15) | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-20.html#h-20}}</ref>
* unincorporated associations
* corporations (including income trusts, but excluding banks, insurance companies, trust companies, loan companies and railway companies)
* cooperative societies and organizations
* successors of partnerships, associations, corporations societies and organizations
* heirs, executors, liquidators of the succession, administrators or other legal representatives of a person <ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, S. 2, definitions of "person" and "corporation" | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-1.html#h-2}}</ref>

The CCAA covers insolvent companies (together with their affiliates) with debts greater than $5 million. <ref>{{Cite web|title = CCAA, S. 3 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-36/page-2.html#h-3}}</ref>

The ''Winding-Up and Restructuring Act'' covers financial institutions not covered by the BIA. <ref>{{Cite web|title = Winding-Up and Restructuring Act, S. 6(1) | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/W-11/page-3.html#h-3}}</ref>

The ''Canada Transportation Act'' covers railway companies. <ref>{{Cite web|title = Canada Transportation Act, S. 106 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-10.4/page-33.html#h-58}}</ref>

