The estate is then settled, using the priority of claims outlined in the [[Bankruptcy and Insolvency Act|BIA]].

==Companies' Creditors Arrangements Act (CCAA) proceedings==

The CCAA has been described as being similar in nature to [[Chapter 11, Title 11, United States Code | Chapter 11]] proceedings in the United States and to [[Administration (law) | administration proceedings]] and [[Insolvency Act 1986 | company voluntary arrangements]] ("CVAs") in the United Kingdom. That is not quite correct, and the differences are highlighted as shown below:

{| border="1" cellpadding="5" cellspacing="0" align="center" style="margin: 1em auto 1em auto;"
! scope="col" width="75" |  '''Action'''
! scope="col" width="150"|  '''CCAA (Canada)'''
! scope="col" width="150"|  '''Chapter 11 (US)'''<ref>{{Cite web|title = Chapter 11, US Bankruptcy Code (from Cornell LII) | url = http://www.law.cornell.edu/uscode/11/usc_sup_01_11_10_11.html}}</ref>
