==Creation of security interests==

It is in the lender's or supplier's best interest to minimize his financial exposure should his client experience financial difficulties. To that end, there is a range of remedies available to establish his status as a secured (vs unsecured) creditor under both provincial and federal legislation.<ref>{{Cite web|author = John R. Sandrelli, Christopher J. Ramsay and Anjili I. Bahadoorsingh |title = Remedies under Security Interests in Canada: An Overview | url= http://www.fmc-law.com/upload/en/publications/archive/12619_Remedies_under_Security_IBA_pdf.PDF | publisher = [[Fraser Milner Casgrain]] | date = 2002-09-18 | accessdate = 2011-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Federal Security Interests: Contract #99-08-2 | url= http://dalspace.library.dal.ca/bitstream/handle/10222/10278/Fraser%20Milner%20Casgrain%20Research%20Security%20Interests%20EN.pdf?sequence=1 | publisher = [[Fraser Milner Casgrain]] under contract to the Law Commission of Canada| date = 2000-06 | accessdate = 2011-09-14}}</ref>

In the common-law provinces, security interests are created through the registration of [[mortgage law | mortgages and charges]] against the real property concerned. In Qu<U+00E9>bec, this is done by way of [[hypothec]]s against immoveable property.

For personal property (moveable property in Qu<U+00E9>bec), secured creditors create their security interests through registration under the ''[[Personal Property Security Act]]'' ("PPSA") in force in their province, or under the ''[[Civil Code of Quebec|Civil Code]]'' in Qu<U+00E9>bec through the ''Registre des droits personnels et r<U+00E9>els mobiliers''.<ref>{{Cite web|author = Kiriakoula Hatzikiriako |title = An attempt to "demystify" Qu<U+00E9>bec secured transactions law (Part I) | url= http://www.mcmillan.ca/Files/ARTICLE_An%20attempt%20to%20demystify_ABA_E_0610.pdf | publisher = ABA Commercial Law Newsletter as reprinted by [[McMillan LLP]] | date = Summer 2010 | accessdate = 2011-09-13}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Registre des droits personnels et r<U+00E9>els mobiliers | url= http://www.justice.gouv.qc.ca/english/programmes/rdprm-a.htm| accessdate = 2011-09-13}}</ref> Banks can also create security interests under SS. 426-427 of the [[Canada Bank Act | Bank Act]],<ref>{{Cite web|title = Bank Act (S.C. 1991, c. 46), S. 426 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-1.01/page-125.html}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Bank Act (S.C. 1991, c. 46), S. 427 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-1.01/page-126.html}}</ref> which normally have priority over PPSA registrations.<ref>{{Cite web|author = Rebecca M. Morse |title = Priority Disputes between the Bank Act and Provincial PPSA Legislation | url= http://www.farris.com/images/uploads/RMM_-_Article_-_Priority_Disputes_Between_the_Bank_Act_and_Provincial_PPSA_Legislation.pdf | publisher = Farris, Vaughan, Wills & Murphy LLP | accessdate = 2011-09-13}}</ref>

There can be complex interplay between insolvency law and other legal regimes, such as [[admiralty law]].<ref>{{Cite web|author = Robert A. Margolis and Christopher J. Giaschi |title = Priorities and Bankruptcy in Admiralty | url= http://www.admiraltylaw.com/papers/bankruptcy.pdf | date = 2002-04 | accessdate = 2011-09-22}}</ref>

==Debtor protection provisions==

No person may terminate or amend <U+2014> or claim an accelerated payment or forfeiture of the term under <U+2014> any agreement, including a security agreement, with a bankrupt individual by reason only of the individual<U+2019>s bankruptcy or insolvency. <ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, S. 84.2 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-63.html}}</ref> Similar provision is made with respect to any insolvent person upon filing a notice of intention or a proposal, <ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, S. 65.1 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-33.html}}</ref> as well as for any debtor company subject to the CCAA by reason only by reason only that proceedings commenced under the CCA or that the company is insolvent. <ref>{{Cite web|title = CCAA, S. 34(1) | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-36/page-20.html}}</ref> Because of these restrictions on what are called ''"ipso facto"'' clauses, creditors must be careful in specifying appropriate trigger events in their contracts' termination clauses. <ref>{{Cite web| author = Stephen J. Weisz |title = Insolvency and Restructuring Agreements in an Economic Downturn | url = http://www.blakes.com/english/publications/RI/pdf/Paper139.pdf | publisher = [[Blake, Cassels & Graydon]] | date = 2009-04 | accessdate = 2011-09-07}}</ref>

A notice of intention <ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, S. 50.4 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-25.html}}</ref> or a Division I proposal <ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, S. 62(1) | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-30.html}}</ref> will automatically create a stay of proceedings and "no creditor has any remedy against the debtor or the debtor<U+2019>s property, or shall commence or continue any action, execution or other proceedings, for the recovery of a claim provable in bankruptcy". Similar provision is also made on the bankruptcy of any debtor. <ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, S. 69.3 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-51.html}}</ref> Directors of insolvent companies that have filed a notice of intention or a proposal have similar protection. <ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, S. 69.31 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-52.html}}</ref>

Contracts may be assigned elsewhere in the event of a notice of intention of a Division I proposal<ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, S. 66(1.1) | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-37.html}}</ref>, bankruptcy<ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, S. 84.1 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-63.html}}</ref> or CCAA proceeding<ref>{{Cite web|title = CCAA, S. 11.3 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-36/page-9.html}}</ref>. Agreements of any kind can be disclaimed in the event of a Division I proposal<ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, S. 65.11 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-34.html}}</ref> or CCAA proceeding<ref>{{Cite web|title = CCAA, S. 32 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-36/page-19.html#h-10}}</ref>, as well as leases in a bankruptcy proceeding<ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, S. 30(1)(k) | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-15.html}}</ref>.

Critical suppliers may be ordered to continue dealing with companies undergoing a CCAA proceeding, if the goods or services supplied are critical to the company's continued operation<ref>{{Cite web|title = CCAA, S. 11.4 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-36/page-9.html}}</ref>.

==Anti-avoidance provisions==

As in other countries, certain debtors may be tempted to bypass the process outlined above through the transfer of assets from an insolvent company to a [[phoenix company]], thus abandoning outstanding liabilities to creditors. Recent legal developments have made this procedure unattractive, through creditors using the [[oppression remedy]] available under the CBCA and similar provincial corporations legislation. <ref>{{Cite web| author = Mark Wiffen |title = getting blood from a stone <U+2013> enforcing unpaid corporate judgments against directors | url = http://www.mcmillan.ca/95997 | publisher = [[McMillan LLP]] | date = 2011-07 | accessdate = 2011-09-04}}</ref>

Several procedures are available for investigating companies' behaviour during times of insolvency or other financial difficulty. The BIA provides for examination of relevant parties during the administration of the estate,<ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, SS. 161-167 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-85.html#h-47 | accessdate = 2011-09-15}}</ref> and the CBCA and similar provincial corporations legislation provides for the court to appoint inspectors to investigate and report back on fraudulent, dishonest, oppressive or unfairly prejudicial behaviour of a corporation.<ref>{{Cite web|title = CBCA, Part XIX | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-44/page-74.html#h-27 | accessdate = 2011-09-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web| author = Edmond F.B. Lamek and Andrew Derksen |title = OBA Remedies Fast Forward - OBCA (and CBCA) Inspectors | url = http://www.fasken.com/files/Publication/10ff42fd-2a1b-425c-ad7f-25cc5d879f0c/Presentation/PublicationAttachment/fdd631fe-9cc3-42e5-b023-30a0c09714d3/OBCA_and_CBCA_Inspectors.pdf | publisher = [[Fasken Martineau]] | accessdate = 2011-09-15}}</ref> A typical inspector's report can be viewed [http://documentcentre.eycan.com/eycm_library/Carling%5CEnglish%5CInspector%27s%20Reports%5CCarling%20Inspector%20-%201st%20Report%20-%20Aug%2016%20with%20Appendices.pdf here.]<ref>{{Cite web| title = Carling (Inspector under Business Corporations Act) | url = http://documentcentre.eycan.com/Pages/Main.aspx?SID=28 | publisher = [[Ernst & Young]] | accessdate = 2011-09-15}}</ref>

Where bankruptcy is sought, it does not necessarily wipe the slate clean on certain debts. Some liabilities are not released upon discharge.<ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, S. 178(1) | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-93.html}}</ref> Directors and parties related to the bankrupt may still be held personally liable for certain tax debts, <ref>{{Cite web| author = Katherine M. Wellburn and Murray Jamieson |title = Taking it all away - Traps set for debtors trying to dodge the taxman | url = http://www.canadianlawsite.ca/Bankruptcy_Paper_Taxes.pdf | date = 2008-09-18/19 | accessdate = 2011-08-25}}</ref> and directors can be held accountable for other liabilities. <ref>{{Cite web| author = David A. DeGroot |title = Directors' liability during corporate insolvency | url = http://www.bdplaw.com/titanweb/bdp/bdpwebsite.nsf/AllDoc/8981B19B11CADABD852575ED006F9D18/$File/BDP%20Insolvency%20&%20Restructuring%20NL%20June%2009.pdf | publisher = Burnett, Duckworth & Palmer LLP | date = 2009-06 | accessdate = 2011-09-04}}</ref>

Certain bankruptcy and CCAA proceedings involve the issue of unpaid wages, severance and termination pay, and other payroll liabilities. The ''Wage Earner Protection Program Act'' <ref>{{Cite web|title = Wage Earner Protection Program Act (S.C. 2005, c. 47, s. 1)) | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/W-0.8/index.html | accessdate = 2011-09-04}}</ref> provides a procedure to claim a portion of the amount due, against which the "super-priority" of the employees on the assets of the estate is subrogated. <ref>{{Cite web|title = Wage Earner Protection Program | url = http://www.servicecanada.gc.ca/eng/sc/wepp/index.shtml | accessdate = 2011-09-04}}</ref>

==Removal of directors==

The court has power to remove one or more of the company's directors, if the court is satisfied that the director is unreasonably impairing or is likely to unreasonably impair the possibility of a viable proposal (or in the case of the CCAA, a compromise or arrangement) being made in respect of the company or is acting or is likely to act inappropriately as a director in the circumstances. <ref>{{Cite web|title = BIA, s. 64 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/B-3/page-31.html}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = CCAA, s. 11.5 | url = http://laws-lois.justice.gc.ca/eng/acts/C-36/page-10.html}}</ref>

